collection: Bronze palstave discovered at Burton Green, a village on high ground 2 1/2 miles North West of Kenilworth, shortly before the 1914-18 war. It has remained ever since in the possession of its finder, Mr. W. A. Beamish, a builder of Hampton-in-Arden, but has been on exhibition at the Birmingham Art Gallery 1928-34 and 1934-36 at the Coventry Museum.
composition: Copper (81%),Tin (11%),Lead(0.9%),Zinc (2.7%),Iron and aluminum present but not determined. Not assayed, arsenic, antimony, phosphorus.
remarks: N.B.: These particulars enclosed in a letter dated 25th Sept. 1944, from Mr. W. A. Seaby, Keeper of the City Museum and Art Gallery, Birmingham, to the Secretary Smith of [...] London. In this letter it is states that the palstave is being published by Professor H.F. Humphreys, FSA in the Transactions of the Birmingham Archeological Society for 1941-1942.

description: Discovered by workmen digging a drainage inspection box immediately to the south of the front door of "Seaward", The Ridings, East Preston (TQ 068018). Found 18 inches deep in clay mould. Found July, 1954.,Late Bronze Age palstave with stop-ridge and loop. Two raised ribs below and almost at right angles to stop-ridge. Both flanges on one side damaged.
remarks: One of nine implements found at "Seaward" by workmen. This, and one small fragment of a palstave were brought to my notice at the Museum; extensive enquiries, however, failed to trace any others which were reputed to have been 'sold to a dealer for sixpence'; etc. The building firm concerned, also, was most un-cooperative. The workmen were questioned as to the appearance of the others and from their description it appears to have been a hoard of eight palstaves and one socketed axe.

other: These people were really random about filling in cards!

The workmen were questioned as to the appearance of the others and from their description it appears to have been a hoard of eight palstaves and one socketed axe.

remarks: Purchased by Hull Museum in Sussex, and said to have been part of a hoard found in Kent. site: england,somerset,taunton,(near taunton).,found 1934 in digging post hole in sand of a small holding known as "mount pleasant" c 600 ft above sea level. "mount pleasant" is not named on 6" o.s. lxxx s.w., but it is the building 530 yds sse of curland church, &, as the crow flies, only 680 yds nne of the "beacon" od castle neroche (see proc: som: arch: soc: xlix. ii 23-53). the impt. was found by dg. dicks, the owner of the building, at a depth of 3 ft.
description: The flanges taper from the prominent stop ridge towards the butt: on both faces of the palstave is a well defined tongue shaped ridge which protrudes from the stop ridge towards the cutting edge. The fin down the middle of both sides (casting mark) has not been entirely removed. Both the cutting edge & the butt have been considerably hammered. In places the bright surface of the bronze indicates "polishing up" by the finder.

collection: Taunton Caste,Somerset County Museum, presented April 1935,Mr. Dicks the finder, give it to Dr. Fawars of Chard, who gave it to the Museum.
description: The flanges taper from the prominent stop ridge towards the butt: on both faces of the palstave is a well-defined [tongue?] shaped ridge which protrudes from the stop ridge towards the cutting edge. The fin down the middle of both sides (casting mark) has not been entirely removed. Both the cutting edge and the butt have been considerably hammered. In places the bright surface of the bronze indicates "polishing up" by finder.
remarks: Found in 1934 in digging port hole in yard of a small holding known as "Mount Pleasant" c. 600 feet above sea level. "Mount Pleasant" is not named on 6"0-S. LXXX S.W., but it is the building 530 yards SSE of Curland Church, and, as the crow flies, only 680 yards NNW of the "Beacon" of Castle Neroche (see Proc. Som. Arch. Soc. XLIX ii 23-53). The impt. was found by D.G. Dicks, the owner of the building, at a depth of 3 ft.

"I have this day forwarded to your address the Battle Axes...they were dug up in 'Winterhay Green' which was a small common in the parish of Ilminster, when my brother was having his allotment drained. There were 2 ornaments of gold...It was rolled up in a [bundle?] but when opened it was a long strip of gold, about, about 1/4 of an inch in width, with a kind of crook at the end to fasten with. It was a very large piece and weighed about the weight of 2 guineas; if I recollect right there were 2 similar pieces."

surface: Patina black-brown/mid-brown mottled - largely intact; flaked in patches towards edge and bt. and a little on fg. crests to dull brown with some brightish green speckles.
description: Dimensions: L 173.5mm; We 74.9mm; Wbt 25.5mm; Bfg. 32.7mm; Bst (middle) 29.3mm; Tsep 7.7mm; Wt. 590.9 gms,Typology: slightly irregular bev. across fg. tops on sep.; one sep. little wider than other - both curved between in cross-sec., with rounded angles; fg. and stop crests neat rounded - no distinct bevels; stops little depressed in centre; short fg. extensions onto bl. with flattened crests tending to splay at bases; midribs low-rounded bumps with at crisp bevels - one extends virt. to edge bev., other higher, but as short as fg. extensions; slides slightly bowed in cross-sec.,Manufacture: cg. fl. remains as very broad low rounded bump - less pronounced on other side, virt. all trace removed on bl. sides, with some hammer rippling; dimples generally over surface - hammer marks or moulding? Swallow hole in end of one sep., depression in other; e. bevs. little diffuse - assoc. hammermarks,Condition: most of blade edge irregular - probably from chipping of patina, but one large chip def. anc. with patina intact; patina frag. also in one butt depression - irreg line probably original 2 or 3 small gougings of patina - probably recent - including one blade angle, forming facet; short intact stretches of blade edge suggest once fairly sharp,Attached material: chalky fawn 'dust' adhering in parts; some stained orange brown matrix also
remarks: Circumstances: Found Winter 1978/9; actual field from which recovered not remembered by finer, but Susan Limbrey was able to match clayey soil deposits adhering to the axe with soil from Pits Field - the only clayey one in the vicinity; GR based on centre of field. (a)

description: Dimentions: L 154.4mm; We 59.3mm; Wst 32.3mm; Wbt 23.0mm; Bfg 26mm; Bst 27.5mm; Wt. 440.2 gms,Typology: fg. insides well sloped to rounded angles with slightly curved septum floor; end sub-rect.; shield rib begins at lower levels than fg./stop, and divided on either face by central rib; blade sec. near rect. - only slightly bowed faces; one sep rather longer than the other.,Manufacture: some dimpling undulations in patina extant - probably from moulding; cg. flash survives only as slight step, or differential surface condition; diffuse edge bevel probably originally sharp and quite steep,Condition: blade edge a little jagged - quite likely intact corrosion; fissures across base of 3 fgs just above stop - pres. dam.; butt close to orig. shape, but notch uncertain,Attached Material: chalky fawn soil deposit ingrained in patina in sep ends.
publications: a) Salop. S. A. M. Record SA 2663
remarks: Circumstances: Found 10 Sept 1979 by G. Haddock of Shrewsbury and District Metal Detector Society, at depth of 9-12 ", using a metal detector, at Haughmond Fields (a) Landowner J. Wild.

site: shropshire,wem rural,circumstances: found sept. 1979 by mr roberts on the surface of the field while potato lifting in area known as rookery meadows; the field has been ploughed annually in recent years; it is just possible that the axe had been dumped with material dredged from the river roden which borders the field (a)

other: Modern card, fields do not match data entry template, ,
description: Typology: shield depression on blade with no encircling rib; stop thick with round bevel - slightly dipped towards either flange; sl. bar ridges on sides; cross-section - sep. floor curved, inside angles sl. rounded, fg crests rounded; v. diffuse bev. across fg. tops on butt;,Manufacture: butt end a broken sur. from snapping off cg.jet; shallow hole in one sep. end, one half partly filled with more vesicular metal; cg. flash well removed for most part - evident as groove and or ridge; neat high e. bev. plus two (or one on sev.) close to edge; v. sl. blade tip hollows; dimpling in p. on sides and in septums - prob. in the moulding; hammering of tops of two flanges has caused sl. lipping on one side.,Condition: some minor denting of edge, stretches fairly sharp; tips both a little blunted - one retains patina, the other & all of rev. bl. face polished to bright gold colour by finder;  crack across the base of one fg. - dam? - another sur. fissure across one corner of blade;
publications: Bibliog. a) Salop SdM Record - SA2660

collection: Roberts, Mr. D. I. - private,Broom Farm, Stanwondine, Baschurch, Shropshire

remarks: Circumstances: Found Sept. 1979 by Mr. Roberts on the surface of the field while potato lifting - area known as Rockery Meadows: the field has been ploughed annually in recent years; it is just possible that the ace had been dumped with the material dredged from the River Roden which borders the field. (a)
